##Key concepts:

DDoS: Flooding tlds with fake traffic to crash the internet infrastructure

Redirect attacks/DNS poisoning: Injecting fake IP mappings into a DNS cache server, users trying to fo to bank.com are redirected to a malicious
clone page.

DNS amplification: Attckers send small DNS queries to open DNS servers but fake the senders IP to be the victims IP, and then its flooded with massive traffic cuz of 
the dns responses.

Mass traffic manipulation: DNS vulnerabilities allow attacckers to control where traffic flows on a global scale, shifting trust and intercepting user connections without 
touching the victim's actual website.

##Tools:

Scrapy: Powerful python tool used to forge custom, spoofed network packets for amplification attacks.

Wireshark: Used to identify unexpected DNS responses or an overwhelming surge of unsolicited inbound DNS traffic.

##Blue team:
Process: Implement DNSSEC(DNS Security Extensions), which adds cryptographic signatures to DNS records so servers can prove they aren't sending poisoned data. To
prevent amplification attacks, they configure public DNS servers to rate-limit requests.

End Goal: To guaranteee the integrity of DNS and prevent their own servers from being weaponized against others.

##Red team: 
Process: IN DNS posioning, attacker races to send a fake, malicious response to a local DNS resolver before the real server can reply. If they win the race, resolver 
saves the malicious IP mapping and compromises all local users routing through it.

End goal: Transparently intercept traffic, steal user login creds with lookalike pages, or cause widespread DoS.
